In [2]:
date = '20190715'

future = 'IF1907'
stock = '000300.SH'

ft = Table.read_table(date + '/' + future + '_' + date + '_preprocessed_smooth.csv')
st = Table.read_table(date + '/' + stock + '_' + date + '_preprocessed_smooth.csv')

f_index = ft.column('index')
s_index = st.column('index')
times = ft.column('time')
basis = s_index - f_index

freqs = [180, 120, 90, 60, 64, 36, 16, 4] # ticks: 1 tick = 0.5s
MAs, noises = [], []
for i in range(len(freqs)):
    freq = freqs[i]
    if i < 4:
        MAs.append(SMA(basis, freq))
    else:
        MAs.append(HMA(basis, freq))
    noises.append(basis - MAs[-1])

has greater predictability. How to take advantage of it?

Low frequency noise has a better correlation with futures price than high frequency noise.

Increments of both high and low frequency noise have greater interpretability of increments of futures prices than of stock prices, since futures data update 10 times more frequent than stock data.
